            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Theoretical Proof Deep-Dive -->
    <section class="topic-section" style="background: #f8fafc; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 2.5rem;">
        <h2 style="color: #0f172a; margin-top: 0;">üéì The Proof: Why $Sum = -b/a$</h2>
        <p style="color: #475569; margin-bottom: 2rem;">For students aiming for an 800, knowing the "trick" isn't enough. You need to understand the underlying logic. Here is the rigorous derivation:</p>
        
        <div style="background: white; padding: 2rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid #cbd5e1; font-family: serif; font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 2;">
            <p>1. Start with the generic quadratic equation: $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$</p>
            <p>2. According to the <strong>Quadratic Formula</strong>, the two solutions ($x_1$ and $x_2$) are:</p>
            <div style="text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0; font-size: 1.4rem;">
                $x_1 = \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$ &nbsp; and &nbsp; $x_2 = \frac{-b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$
            </div>
            <p>3. Let $D$ represent the discriminant ($b^2 - 4ac$):</p>
            <div style="text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
                $x_1 = \frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a}, \quad x_2 = \frac{-b - \sqrt{D}}{2a}$
            </div>
            <p>4. Add the two roots together to find the <strong>Sum</strong>:</p>
            <div style="text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0; font-size: 1.4rem; color: #1e40af;">
                $Sum = \frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a} + \frac{-b - \sqrt{D}}{2a}$
            </div>
            <p>5. Combine the fractions over the common denominator $2a$:</p>
            <div style="text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
                $Sum = \frac{-b + \sqrt{D} - b - \sqrt{D}}{2a}$
            </div>
            <p>6. Notice that $+\sqrt{D}$ and $-\sqrt{D}$ cancel out perfectly:</p>
            <div style="text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0; font-weight: bold;">
                $Sum = \frac{-2b}{2a}$
            </div>
            <p>7. Simplify the fraction:</p>
            <div style="text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0; font-size: 1.5rem; color: #10b981;">
                $Sum = -\frac{b}{a}$
            </div>
            <p style="text-align: right; font-style: italic; color: #64748b; margin-top: 1rem;">Q.E.D. ‚Äî This is why the shortcut works for EVERY quadratic equation.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

